 The first anthology of its kind, Radiant Truths gathers an exquisite selection of writings by both well-known and forgotten American authors and thinkers, each engaged in the challenges of writing about religion, of documenting “things unseen.” Their contributions to the genre of literary journalism—the telling of factual stories using the techniques of fiction and poetry—make this volume one of the most exciting anthologies of creative nonfiction to have emerged in years.   Jeff Sharlet presents an evocative selection of writings that illuminate the evolution of the American genre of documentary prose. Each entry may be savored separately, but together the works enrich one another, engaging in an implicit and continuing conversation that reaches across time and generations.Including works by: Walt Whitman  •  Henry David Thoreau  •  Mark Twain  •  Meridel Le Sueur  •  Zora Neale Hurston  •  Mary McCarthy  •  James Baldwin  •  Norman Mailer  •  Ellen Willis  •  Anne Fadiman  •  John Jeremiah Sullivan  •  Francine Prose  •  Garry Wills  •  and many others    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aElectronic books. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Essays.2bisacsh1 aAddams, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaldwin, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCahan, Abraham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCovington, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncan, Sara Jeannette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFadiman, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrizzuti Harrison, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHurston, Zora Neale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary